value.0: This ring identifies one as belonging to the Cordor Tradesman Guild Local 120.  Merchants customarily will offer slight discounts to other guildmembers.

Northeast - Shire of Bendir Dale, Amia Forest

Northwest - Forest of Despair
This partially-decayed body is dressed in the ruined clothing of a well-to-do merchant of Cordor.
With the face turned down, it's hard to determine if the victim was male or female.
Small, delicate white flowers.  Maybe the tailor in Cordor would know what this is.

The plant upon which the ever-popular sweetberry grows. Fairly small-sized, these plants have been known to grow larger when cultivated as house plants; this practice is rather uncommon, however, perhaps because of the fey that are usually attracted to houses in which the plants are potted....

The Sweetberry is a highly prized item for Cordorian children, to others, completely useless.  Commonly stuck on the end of a stick and licked, the sweetberry has a powerfully sweet taste that most adults find overwhelming.  Except in Amia, where they are enjoyed by almost all, sometimes even a little too much, in the case of an ex-assassin who craves them with a passion.

Dogma of Gruumsh: Seek unceasing war against your enemies, and kill or enslave those that oppose you. Acquire territory and living space. Destroy elves, their homes, and their lands. Crush the dwarves and take their deep caves for your own. Be strong, and be prepared to show your strength at any moment. Showing weakness is the key to an early death. Those that are too weak to fight for your tribe should be put to the spear. The greatest gift that He Who Watches gave to the orcs was the ability to survive where the weaker races would die. Build your strength in these lands and use them to overrun your enemies.

From Clebrior's Flora: 

"Aconite, or Wolf's Bane is a species of Aconitum, native and endemic to western and central Amia.

It is a herbaceous perennial plant growing to 1 m tall, with hairless stems and leaves. The leaves are rounded, 5-10 cm diameter, palmately divided into five to seven deeply lobed segments. The flowers are dark purple to bluish-purple, narrow oblong helmet-shaped, 1-2 cm tall.

Like other species in the genus, it is extremely poisonous, generating enough poison to be used to tip spears and arrows for hunting and battle."
